SABOOR - INVESTING STRATEGY
===========================

Goal: Beat the S&P 500 (SPY) over time through disciplined, halal, Buffett-style ownership of excellent businesses.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
THE THESIS
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Saboor is a business-owner system, not a trading system.

It buys companies that are understandable, sharia-compliant, financially strong,
well-managed, and capable of compounding value over years. Momentum may improve
entry timing, but it is never the reason to own a business. News is useful only
when it changes the economics of the company.

The Analyst has discretion inside strict boundaries. It decides whether to Buy,
Add, Hold, Trim, or Exit, but every decision must be explained through business
quality, moat, balance sheet, valuation, forward expected return, sharia status,
and portfolio concentration.

Saboor does not force deployment. Cash is a valid position when the opportunity
set is weak.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
INVESTABLE UNIVERSE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
The investable universe starts with a curated S&P 500 + NASDAQ 100 list.

Conventional banks, insurance, alcohol, tobacco, weapons manufacturers,
gambling, adult entertainment, and pork-related businesses are excluded before
capital is committed.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
SHARIA COMPLIANCE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Every stock must pass a two-layer sharia review before purchase:

1. Bulk screen (pre-market)
   Claude classifies universe tickers by primary business activity using AAOIFI
   criteria:
   - non_compliant: excluded for the session
   - compliant: may proceed
   - needs_review: passed to deeper Analyst review

2. Deep check (Analyst phase)
   The Analyst reviews business activity and financial ratios using the
   available yfinance dossier and any existing position context:
   - Interest-bearing debt should be below AAOIFI tolerance
   - Interest income should be immaterial
   - Primary business activity must be halal

Any stock that fails sharia review cannot be bought or added to. If an existing
holding later becomes non-compliant, the Analyst must recommend an orderly exit.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
LONG-ONLY MANDATE
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Saboor is a long-only business-owner system.

It never opens short positions, uses margin, uses leverage, trades options,
or buys inverse ETFs. If the Analyst dislikes a company, the only valid
response is Hold Cash or Avoid — never Short.

This is enforced in code: any sell order for a ticker with no existing long
position in Alpaca is blocked by Risk Guardian before it reaches the broker.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
HARD ENTRY FILTERS
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
These filters are enforced in code for new buys and adds. Claude cannot
override them:

  RSI > 78
    Blocked. The stock is overbought and reversal risk is high.

  Price > 150% above MA200
    Blocked. The stock is dangerously extended.

  FCF negative AND PE > 150x AND ROE negative
    Blocked. This is speculation without a fundamental floor.

  Position would exceed 14% of portfolio value
    Blocked. Concentration is allowed, domination by one name is not.

  Sell order with no long position in Alpaca
    Blocked. Prevents accidental short positions.

These are entry filters. They are not automatic sell triggers.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
BUSINESS QUALITY MODEL
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Analyst should evaluate each company as a business first:

  Circle of competence
    Is the business understandable enough for Saboor to own it?

  Moat
    Does the company have durable competitive advantages such as network
    effects, switching costs, brand strength, cost advantage, distribution, or
    data/AI advantages that translate into real economics?

  Financial quality
    Revenue growth, gross margin, return on equity, free cash flow durability,
    debt load, capital intensity, and reinvestment runway.

  Management and capital allocation
    Does management allocate capital rationally? Are buybacks, debt, M&A, and
    reinvestment decisions sensible?

  AI-era impact
    AI is not a magic word. The Analyst must decide whether AI strengthens or
    weakens the actual business economics:
    - Does AI expand the moat?
    - Does it reduce costs structurally?
    - Does it increase pricing power?
    - Does it create new demand?
    - Does it disrupt the company's product or margin structure?

  Valuation
    Is the current price sensible relative to owner earnings, free cash flow,
    growth quality, and downside risk?

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
SCORING MODEL
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Scores are aids to judgment, not substitutes for judgment.

QUALITY SCORE (0-100):
  Revenue growth YoY   >20% = 25 | 10-20% = 15 | <10% = 5 | negative = 0
  Gross margin         >50% = 20 | 30-50% = 12 | <30% = 5
  Return on Equity     >20% = 20 | 10-20% = 12 | <10% = 5 | negative = -10
  Debt / Equity        <0.3 = 20 | 0.3-1.0 = 12 | >1.0 = 5
  Free Cash Flow       positive = 10 | negative = 0
  PEG ratio            <1.5 = 5 | 1.5-2.5 = 3 | >2.5 = 0 | N/A = 2
  Penalty: FCF negative + PE > 100x -> subtract 10 from quality score

ENTRY TIMING SCORE (0-100):
  Price above 50-day MA    yes = 25 | no = 0
  Price above 200-day MA   yes = 25 | no = 0
  RSI (14-day)             40-65 = 25 | 65-72 = 15 | 72-78 = 5
  Volume vs 20-day avg     above = 15 | below = 0
  30-day return vs SPY     outperforming = 10 | underperforming = 0

The entry timing score can help decide whether to buy now, wait, or add slowly.
It must not turn a weak business into a buy.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
PORTFOLIO CONSTRUCTION
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Saboor has one portfolio. There is no tactical bucket.

There is no fixed target number of holdings. Position count is an output of
conviction, account size, opportunity quality, and valuation.

Guidance by account size:

  Under $5k       3-5 positions
  $5k-$25k        4-8 positions
  $25k-$100k      5-10 positions
  $100k+          6-12 positions

These ranges are not quotas. Saboor should not buy mediocre companies just to
fill slots. If only three great opportunities exist, hold three. If none exist,
hold cash.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
POSITION SIZING
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Position weight is based on conviction, business quality, valuation, and risk.

Maximum position size:
  14% of total portfolio value.

Minimum position size:
  No formal percentage minimum. However, Saboor should avoid token positions
  that are too small to matter relative to account size and monitoring effort.

Suggested initial sizing:

  Exceptional business, attractive valuation, >12% expected return
    10-14%

  Strong business, good valuation, 10-12% expected return
    6-10%

  Good business, reasonable valuation, 7-10% expected return
    3-6%

  Below hurdle or uncertain
    0%; hold cash and wait

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
ORDER CONSOLIDATION AND REPEAT-BUY CONTROL
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
When Saboor decides to buy a new stock, the intended position should be opened
in one deliberate order for the full approved initial size, subject only to
cash, liquidity, broker, and the 14% position cap constraints.

Saboor must not split the same buy decision into multiple small buys minutes
apart. Buying the same ticker twice within a few minutes at nearly the same
price is duplicate execution, not disciplined investing.

For the same ticker, after any Buy or Add order is filled, another Buy/Add for
that ticker is blocked unless at least one of these conditions is true:

  Time separation
    At least 24 hours have passed since the previous filled Buy/Add order.

  Price improvement
    The new execution price is at least 2% below the previous filled Buy/Add
    price, creating a real valuation benefit.

  Exceptional change
    A material new fact changes the thesis or expected return, and the Analyst
    explicitly explains why immediate additional capital is justified.

The default behavior is simple: decide the desired exposure first, then place
one order for that exposure. If Saboor wants a 6% DELL position, it should buy
the 6% position once, not buy 3% and then another 3% two minutes later without
a genuine change in price or facts.

Staging into a position is allowed only when it is intentional and documented.
The Analyst must state the planned tranche size, the condition for the next
tranche, and why staging is better than a single order. The next tranche must
still satisfy the 24-hour, 2% price-improvement, or exceptional-change rule.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
ACTIONS
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
The Analyst may recommend five actions:

  Buy
    Open a new position when business quality, sharia status, valuation, and
    expected return justify ownership.

  Add
    Increase an existing position when the thesis is intact or stronger, the
    valuation remains attractive, and the position stays below the 14% cap.
    Adding can happen after a price decline or a price increase, but never
    because of price alone.

  Hold
    Do nothing when the thesis is intact and expected return remains acceptable.

  Trim
    Reduce a position when the business is still good but valuation is stretched,
    the position has grown too large relative to risk, conviction has softened,
    or a clearly better opportunity exists. Trims are discretionary, not
    automatic rebalancing.

  Exit
    Close the position when the thesis breaks, sharia status changes, intrinsic
    value falls materially, or forward expected return becomes unattractive.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
MACRO CONTEXT
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Saboor fetches current macro data at every pre-market and market-open phase:
  - 10-year Treasury yield
  - 3-month T-bill yield
  - Yield curve spread (10yr minus 3mo)

This context is not a trading signal. It is never a reason to buy or sell
on its own. It informs:

  Required margin of safety
    Higher rates raise the bar. A business must offer more to compete with
    a risk-free alternative.

  Forward expected return hurdle
    Base hurdle: 10% annualized.
    When 10-year yield >= 4.5%: hurdle rises to 12%.

  Debt and refinancing risk
    Leveraged companies face higher rollover costs in a high-rate environment.
    The Analyst must assess whether the debt load is sustainable.

  Durability of pricing power
    Inflation tests whether a company can pass costs to customers. The Analyst
    must judge whether margins will hold, compress, or improve.

  Cash preference
    When the opportunity set is weak and rates are high, holding cash is
    explicitly preferable to buying mediocre businesses.

Macro context does not change the buy/sell framework. It tightens or loosens
the valuation discipline applied within that framework.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
INTRINSIC VALUE AND OVERVALUATION
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Saboor does not sell because "the market is greedy." It sells or trims only
when price is no longer justified by business value.

For each owned company, the Analyst must maintain an intrinsic-value band:

  Bear value
    Conservative assumptions for growth, margins, and multiple.

  Base value
    Reasonable owner-earnings or free-cash-flow estimate.

  Bull value
    Optimistic but defensible outcome.

The Analyst must estimate the expected 3-5 year annualized return from
today's price for every candidate and every open position.

Hurdle rate: 10% annualized.
When 10-year Treasury yield >= 4.5%, the effective hurdle rises to 12%.

  Expected return >= hurdle AND thesis intact
    Hold or Add.

  Expected return below hurdle AND business is excellent AND thesis is intact
    Hold. Excellent businesses can stay expensive for long periods.
    Patience is a feature, not a weakness.

  Price materially above base-case intrinsic value AND return is poor
  AND position is large
    Trim. Reduce size, do not exit.

  Expected return well below hurdle AND thesis has weakened
  OR a clearly superior opportunity exists
    Trim or Exit.

  Thesis breaks, sharia changes, moat deteriorates, debt becomes dangerous
    Exit, regardless of price.

Exit is a high bar. Prefer Trim over Exit when the business is still good
but the price is stretched. Never exit solely because of short-term price
weakness, market fear, or macro headlines.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
SELLING RULES
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Price decline alone is not a sell reason. A position down 5%, 10%, or 20%
can still be a hold or add if the business has improved and valuation is
better.

Valid reasons to Trim:
  - Price is materially above the base-case intrinsic value
  - Expected 3-5 year return is below the hurdle rate
  - Position size has become too large relative to risk or conviction
  - A clearly superior opportunity exists

Valid reasons to Exit:
  - Sharia status changes
  - The business thesis breaks
  - Moat weakens structurally
  - Revenue, margins, or free cash flow deteriorate materially
  - Debt or capital allocation becomes dangerous
  - Intrinsic value falls materially
  - Expected return is poor and capital can be better redeployed

Invalid reasons to sell:
  - Short-term price volatility
  - Market-wide drawdown by itself
  - RSI or moving-average weakness alone
  - Macro fear without a change in business economics
  - Headlines that do not change how the business operates or earns

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
DAILY PHASES (Oman time, UTC+4)
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
  3:30 PM  PRE-MARKET    Sharia screen + yfinance research + candidate refresh
                           Telegram silent; candidates are internal only.
  5:35 PM  MARKET OPEN   Buy/Add/Hold/Trim/Exit review through Risk Guardian.
                           Telegram reports only approved/executed trades.
  8:00 PM  MIDDAY        Portfolio monitoring and urgent thesis/compliance checks
 11:30 PM  EOD           Benchmark record. Telegram quiet unless there were
                           buy/sell actions that day.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
TELEGRAM REPORTING
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Telegram is for confirmed action, not possible trades.

Pre-market candidates, watchlists, and "possible trade" ideas must not be sent
to Telegram. They are internal research inputs until the Trader decides and Risk
Guardian approves an actual Buy, Add, Trim, or Exit.

Once a trade is approved and executed, Telegram should report only the executed
stock actions for that day. Stocks that are merely candidates, holds, avoids,
or below threshold should not appear in the Telegram report.

If there are no Buy/Add/Trim/Exit actions for the day, Telegram stays quiet.

Every sent trade report must give a complete explanation for each stock action:
action, ticker, shares, execution price, and the full reason. Reports must be
split into multiple Telegram-safe messages when needed, not truncated in the
middle of a sentence or word.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
WHAT SABOOR NEVER DOES
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
- Trade non-sharia-compliant stocks
- Open short positions, use margin, use leverage, trade options, or buy inverse ETFs
- Buy or add when hard entry filters are triggered
- Buy purely because of momentum
- Sell purely because the price went down
- Sell because macro conditions are scary
- Buy because macro conditions are favorable
- Force capital deployment when opportunities are weak
- Send Telegram reports about possible trades or pre-market candidates
- Truncate Telegram stock explanations mid-sentence or mid-word
- Open meaningless token positions
- Split one buy decision into multiple same-ticker orders minutes apart
- Re-buy or add the same ticker within 24 hours unless price is at least 2%
  better or a material new fact justifies it
- Let one position exceed 14% of portfolio value
- Treat AI hype as a thesis without business-economic evidence
- Exit a good business just because it looks expensive by one metric

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
CLAUDE TRADER PROMPT GUARDRAIL
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Use this prompt in Trader/Analyst instructions when deciding and formatting
orders:

  You are Saboor's Trader. Before recommending any Buy or Add, decide the full
  desired position size first. If the stock should be owned, recommend one
  consolidated order for the full approved size, subject to cash, liquidity,
  broker limits, and the 14% max position cap.

  Do not create duplicate same-ticker buys minutes apart. If there was already
  a filled Buy/Add for this ticker, block another Buy/Add unless at least 24
  hours have passed, or the new price is at least 2% below the previous filled
  Buy/Add price, or a material new fact has changed the thesis and you explain
  it clearly.

  If you intentionally stage into a position, document the tranche plan, the
  next-tranche trigger, and why staging is superior to buying the full intended
  exposure now. A second same-day trade at nearly the same price is not allowed.

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
BENCHMARK
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Daily performance is compared to SPY for tracking, but Saboor is judged over
multi-year periods. Daily alpha is a measurement, not a trading signal.

Alpha, cumulative return, portfolio value, and open positions are tracked in
Supabase and displayed on the dashboard.
